		<div id="siteNotice"><script type='text/javascript'>if (wgNotice != '') document.writeln(wgNotice);</script></div>		<h1 id="firstHeading" class="firstHeading">English orthography</h1>
		<div id="bodyContent">
			<h3 id="siteSub">From Wikipedia, the free encyclopedia</h3>
			<div id="contentSub"></div>
									<div id="jump-to-nav">Jump to: <a href="#column-one">navigation</a>, <a href="#searchInput">search</a></div>			<!-- start content -->
			<p><b>English orthography</b> is the alphabetic <a href="/wiki/Orthography" title="Orthography">spelling</a> system used by the <a href="/wiki/English_language" title="English language">English language</a>. English orthography, like other alphabetic orthographies, uses a set of rules that generally governs how speech sounds are represented in writing. English has relatively complicated spelling rules when compared to other <a href="/wiki/Languages" title="Languages" class="mw-redirect">languages</a> with <a href="/wiki/Alphabet" title="Alphabet">alphabetic</a> orthographies. Because of the complex history of the English language, nearly every sound can be legitimately spelled in more than one way, and many spellings can be pronounced in more than one way.</p>
